The methylene bridge (-CH2-) connecting the two benzene rings in diphenylmethane contributes an increase in melting point due to additional rigidity and increased molecular weight, estimated at +20 °C. The amino (-NH2) group, being an electron-donating group, could also influence the melting point through intermolecular hydrogen bonding, which typically raises the melting point. However, in comparison to the effect of the methylene bridge, the impact of the amino group on melting point is relatively smaller, estimated at +5 °C due to hydrogen bonding potential.
